<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="161" pageId="3" pageNumber="160" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[423,1822,2427,2523]" lastBlockId="4.[319,1718,347,743]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="161" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">
This scale was first reported on coconut in 1924 by 
<collectorName box="[1404,1682,2480,2523]" pageId="3" pageNumber="160">C. W. Edwards</collectorName>
, having been discovered late in December of the previous year. It soon threatened the destruction of the coconut trees in 
<collectingCountry box="[1055,1164,397,439]" name="Guam" pageId="4" pageNumber="161">Guam</collectingCountry>
, as it had destroyed them on Saipan. However, a small black ladybeetle 
<emphasis box="[1137,1149,447,489]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="161">(</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Chapin" authorityName="Chapin" authorityYear="1926" box="[1149,1577,447,489]" class="Insecta" family="Coccidae" genus="Telsimia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="161" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitida">
<emphasis box="[1149,1427,447,489]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="161">Telsimia nitida</emphasis>
Chapin
</taxonomicName>
) which was found to be feeding on the scale prevented the catastrophe. In 1927, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chapin" authorityYear="1926" box="[322,474,547,591]" class="Insecta" family="Coccidae" genus="Telsimia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="161" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitida">
<emphasis box="[322,474,547,591]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="161">T. nitida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was reported to have effected complete control of this scale in 
<collectingCountry box="[1603,1711,547,591]" name="Guam" pageId="4" pageNumber="161">Guam</collectingCountry>
. In 1936, no infestations were found, and only small colonies were occasionally found on coconut leaves, banana, grape, mango, 
<taxonomicName box="[1194,1350,651,691]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apocynaceae" genus="Ochrosia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="4" pageNumber="161" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1194,1350,651,691]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="161">Ochrosia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
fruits, and avocado. Reported also on papaya and 
<emphasis box="[866,1142,702,743]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="161">Dioscoreaalata</emphasis>
by Oakley.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
